    <!-- Article Content -->
    <article class="mt-20 prose dark:prose-invert max-w-4xl border-t border-hairline pt-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-6">Demystifying Weighted and Unweighted Grade Point Average Calculations</h2>
      <div class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>
          Your Grade Point Average (GPA) is a standard mathematical metric that colleges, universities, and high schools use to evaluate your overall academic performance. While simple average calculations are standard, grading frameworks differ depending on the school's guidelines.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Weighted vs. Unweighted GPA Scales</h3>
        <p>
          Understanding how scales differ is vital for planning class loads:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-3 font-sans text-sm">
          <li>
            <strong>Unweighted GPA (0 to 4.0 Scale):</strong> Calculates your GPA by mapping letter grades directly to standard values: A=4.0, B=3.0, C=2.0, D=1.0, and F=0.0. Course rigor (difficulty) is ignored, treating a grade in an Advanced Placement (AP) physics class identical to a grade in a regular physical education class.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Weighted GPA (0 to 5.0+ Scale):</strong> Accounts for academic rigor. Honors courses receive an extra +0.5 weight boost, and AP/IB courses receive a full +1.0 grade point boost. Consequently, students taking high-rigor classes can achieve GPA scores well above 4.0, which college admissions boards parse to measure academic commitment.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">The Mathematical Credit-Weight Equation</h3>
        <p>
          GPA is calculated as a <strong>weighted average</strong>, where course credit hours act as weights. You cannot calculate GPA by simply adding letter grade values and dividing by the number of courses. Instead, you multiply each course's grade points by its credit hours to calculate quality points, sum them up, and divide by the total credit hours:
          <br />
          <strong class="block my-2 text-center text-ink font-mono text-xs">GPA = Sum of (Grade Points &times; Credits) / Total Credit Hours</strong>
          This means a grade earned in a 4-credit lecture class has double the numerical impact on your GPA than a grade earned in a 2-credit lab course.
        </p>
      
<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Weighted vs. Unweighted GPAs Explained</h3>
        <p>
          When tracking your academic progress, it is important to understand the difference between weighted and unweighted GPAs. An unweighted GPA is calculated on a standard 4.0 scale, where an A is worth 4 points, a B is 3 points, a C is 2 points, and a D is 1 point, regardless of the class difficulty. A weighted GPA, however, awards extra points for advanced coursework. Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate (IB), and Honors courses are typically graded on a 5.0 scale, where an A is worth 5 points. This means a student taking a challenging course load can achieve a GPA higher than 4.0, which college admissions boards take into account.
        </p>
        <p>
          Additionally, you should know if your school uses a plus/minus grading system. In these systems, grades like an A- or a B+ carry fractional point values (e.g., an A- is worth 3.7 points), which changes the final GPA calculation.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Walkthrough: Projecting a Target Cumulative GPA</h3>
        <p>
          Let's walk through how to project a target GPA. Suppose you are in your junior year with a cumulative GPA of 3.2 over 60 credits, and you want to raise it to a 3.4 by graduation.
        </p>
        <p>
          First, open the Cumulative GPA Planner in our calculator. Input your current cumulative GPA (3.2) and current credits (60). Next, input your planned credits for the remaining semesters (e.g., 30 credits). The calculator will calculate that you need to earn a 3.8 average over your remaining classes to reach your target GPA, helping you track your progress and set academic goals.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">The Impact of GPAs on Financial Aid and Scholarships</h3>
        <p>
          Your cumulative GPA has a direct impact on your eligibility for financial aid and academic scholarships. Under the federal Satisfactory Academic Progress (SAP) guidelines, students must maintain a minimum GPA (usually 2.0 on a 4.0 scale) to keep their financial aid. Many private and institutional scholarships require much higher GPA minimums (such as 3.0 or 3.5). Monitoring your GPA using our calculator allows you to plan your academic progress and ensure you maintain funding throughout college.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">How College Admissions Boards Evaluate GPAs</h3>
        <p>
          College admissions offices do not look at GPA scores in isolation. They evaluate your grades in the context of your course rigor—meaning they check if you took advanced courses when they were available at your school. A student with a 3.6 weighted GPA who took multiple AP classes is often viewed more favorably than a student with a 3.9 unweighted GPA who took only basic courses. Keeping your GPA high while taking a balanced course load is key for college applications.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

  <Sources sources={[
    { label: 'U.S. Department of Education', url: 'https://www.ed.gov/' },
    { label: 'Purdue Online Writing Lab (OWL) — APA/MLA/Chicago', url: 'https://owl.purdue.edu/' }
  ]} />

